    <documentation>
Copyright 2014 Control4.  All rights reserved.

 ***** The WoW Keypad Switch IP Driver *****

This driver serves as the Control4 driver interface to Unique Automation's WoW Keypad Switch.

***** FEATURES *****

The following features are supported through Control4 programming:

* Button events for the first nine buttons.  These events are: change, press, release.  A typical
sequence of events will look like this: press, change, release, change.
* Commands to put the WoW Keypad display into sleep or wake mode.
* Activation of the six available display pages on the keypad.
* The ability to write to the 22 fields available on the display.
* Tag substitution used in the display fields for a guest's name and the outside temperature.
* Five string variables and ten integer variables are available and corresponding tags for 
substitution in a display string.

***** USAGE *****

Properties Page:

* Field_One through Field_Twenty_Two: These are the available text fields in the display.  Each field 
can include substitution tags (see below for more on substitution tags).  When you set the field text
the keypad display is updated.
* Guest_Name: The name of the checked-in guest.  This corresponds to the substitution tag: %GN%.  The
property is read/write so that the tag substitution can be tested.  This property will be overwritten
by a check-in or check-out of a guest.
* S0 through S4: String variables available in programming.  They use the substitution tags:
%S0% through %S4%.
* N0 through N9: integer variables 0 through 10000 available in programming.  These use the 
substitution tags %N0% through %N9%.

***** SUBSTITUTION TAGS *****

Substitution tags are used to substitute a tag with a meaningful value.  For example, if you set the 
value of S0 to "California" and set Field_One to: "Hotel %S0%", the keypad display would scroll the 
following:

"Hotel California"

The value S0 is a Control4 programming variable, so this value can be set programmatically and will
immediately update the keypad display.

Another useful tag is %GN%.  When a guest checks in, their name can be displayed by including the
tag in the text field:

"Welcome %GN%"

Chuck Norris has checked in, therefore the display field using the text above would show:

"Welcome Chuck Norris"

The outside temperature %OT% tag uses the outside temperature provided by the Hospitality Agent:

"Outside: %OT%"

Which would look something like this:

"Outside: 58.0"

The text fields can also be set programmatically in the same way.  Here is an example
of Composer programming:

When a customer checked in.
Activate Page 2 on Room->Wow Keypad
Set Field Two to Welcome %GN% on Room->Wow Keypad

***********************************

    </documentation>
